        Text: {
            transition: "Next",
            text: [
                "<p>So far we’ve only seen powers with positive integer bases, but the base of a power may also be a product.</p>",
                "<p>The power of a product rule allows us to quickly find the result of a product raised to an exponent:</p>",
                "<p>When we have a power raised to an exponent, <b>distribute the exponent</b> to each term in the product.</p>",
                "<p>Using the power of a power rule, we get:</p>",
                "<p>This means we have:</p>",
                {
                    Example: "Math",
                    Content: '(2 \\times 5)^3 = 2^3 \\times 5^3 = 8 \\times 125 = 1000'
                },
                "<p>To see why this is the case, let's take a look at the step that is skipped in the process:</p>",
                {
                    Example: "Math",
                    Content: '(\\frac{2}{5})^3 = (2 \\times 2 \\times 2) \\times (5 \\times 5 \\times 5) = 2^3 \\times 5^3 = 8 \\times 125 = 1000'
                },
                "<p>Done!</p>",
                "<p>The power of a product rule allows us to skip this step and go straight to the simplified exponential form!</p>"
